[1] Nigeria, Ghana, Togo
Date: 11 Dec 2010
Source: This Day [edited]
<http://www.thisdayonline.info/nview.php?id=189695>


The National Root Crops Research Institute (NRCRI) has intensified
efforts to save Nigeria from losing its status as the world's largest
producer of cocoyam by finding solutions to the disease presently
ravaging farms across Nigeria and even beyond.

Cocoyam leaf blight is threatening production, but NRCRI said that
they have commenced research into how the disease could be controlled.
Already, Abia, Ebonyi, Benue and Imo states have been affected by the
disease. "Nigeria is worried about this outbreak," they said.

The head of NRCRI, Nwosu, explained that the disease is caused by the
fungus _Phytophthora colocasiae_ and described the outbreak as
disastrous because "what we've seen in the fields, it can result in
100 percent loss to farmers." The crop is grown for low income
earners. There is growing concern that it could [also] affect other
root crops like yam and cassava.

Nwosu said that the scourge was a sub-regional crisis as it has [also]
been reported in Togo and Ghana. When it appeared in Cameroon, that
government promptly wrote Nigeria to find a lasting solution. NRCRI,
therefore, urged the federal government to declare the disease a
disaster and said that they would partner State Agricultural
Development Programmes (ADP) to reach farmers with short and long term
remedies. The Federal Ministry of Agriculture said that in the next 12
or 24 months, government would come up with remedial measures.

[Byline: Emmanuel Ugwu]

